{"key":"processedPost-9414539","value":{"id":9414539,"first":9412430,"last":9414539,"when":1229043565,"utime":"12/12/08 02:59 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />so i wouldn't have to fan and mist it every day.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Air exchange is the number one pinning trigger.&nbsp; Humidity is farther down the list.&nbsp; Perhaps the number 2 pinning trigger is a loss of moisture from the substrate.&nbsp; If you try to avoid misting by constantly pumping in wet air, you don't have a loss of moisture from the substrate and performance is poor.<br /><br />You want constant air exchange, and then as the cake or other substrate dries out, you mist to replace the lost moisture.&nbsp; This dry-wet cycle is a MAJOR pinning trigger. There is no automated system that can replace your eyeballs and mister.&nbsp; I'm an electrical engineer by profession with a specialty in automation, so believe me when I say if the whole process could be automated, I'd have done it years ago.<br />RR","title":"Re: Coolmist humidifier for FAE and Perlite?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}